
[1]scholar

   SCHOL'AR, n. [Low L. scholaris, from schola, a school; Gr. leisure, a
   school. See School.]

   1. One who learns of a teacher; one who is under the tuition of a
   preceptor; a pupil; a disciple; hence, any member of a college, academy
   or school; applicable to the learner of any art, science or branch of
   literature.

   2. A man of letters.

   3. Emphatically used, a man eminent for erudition; a person of high
   attainments in science or literature.

   4. One that learns any thing; as an apt scholar in the school of vice.

   5. A pedant; a man of books. [But the word scholar seldom conveys the
   idea of a pedant.]
